omplementary approach to psychological interventions. The combination of pharmacological and psychological treatments underscores the importance of a holistic approach to mental health care, addressing both the biological and psychological aspects of mental disorders [Data: Entities (2436, 2435); Relationships (2854, 2859, +more)].\" }, { \"summary\": \"Adaptation disorder and its treatment approaches\", \"explanation\": \"Adaptation disorder is a mental health condition triggered by stressful life events, characterized by emotional and behavioral symptoms. It is often treated with a combination of psychotherapy and pharmacological interventions. Psychotherapy, particularly CBT, helps patients develop coping strategies and modify maladaptive thoughts, while medications like Estazolam and Alprazolam manage symptoms such as anxiety and insomnia. The treatment of adaptation disorder highlights the importance of addressing both the psychological and physiological aspects of mental health conditions [Data: Entities (2431, 2433); Relationships (2848, 2851, +more)].\" } ] }", "refusal": null, "role": "assistant", "annotations": null, "audio": null, "function_call": null, "tool_calls": null}}], "created": 1744255987, "model": "deepseek-v3", "object": "chat.completion", "service_tier": null, "system_fingerprint": null, "usage": {"completion_tokens": 900, "prompt_tokens": 7120, "total_tokens": 8020, "completion_tokens_details": null, "prompt_tokens_details": null}}, "input": {"messages": [{"content": "\nYou are an AI assistant that helps a human analyst to perform general information discovery. Information discovery is the process of identifying and assessing relevant information associated with certain entities (e.g., organizations and individuals) within a network.\n\n# Goal\nWrite a comprehensive report of a community, given a list of entities that belong to the community as well as their relationships and optional associated claims. The report will be used to inform decision-makers about information associated with the community and their potential impact. The content of this report includes an overview of the community's key entities, their legal compliance, technical capabilities, reputation, and noteworthy claims.\n\n# Report Structure\n\nThe report should include the following sections:\n\n- TITLE: community's name that represents its key entities - title should be short but specific. When possible, include representative named entities in the title.\n- SUMMARY: An executive summary of the community's overall structure, how its entities are related to each other, and significant information associated with its entities.\n- IMPACT SEVERITY RATING: a float score between 0-10 that represents the severity of IMPACT posed by entities within the community.  IMPACT is the scored importance of a community.\n- RATING EXPLANATION: Give a single sentence explanation of the IMPACT severity rating.\n- DETAILED FINDINGS: A list of 5-10 key insights about the community. Each insight should have a short summary followed by multiple paragraphs of explanatory text grounded according to the grounding rules below. Be comprehensive.\n\nReturn output as a well-formed JSON-formatted string with the following format:\n    {{\n        \"title\": <report_title>,\n        \"summary\": <executive_summary>,\n        \"rating\": <impact_severity_rating>,\n        \"rating_explanation\": <rating_explanation>,\n        \"findings\": [\n            {{\n                \"summary\":<insight_1_summary>,\n                \"explanation\": <insight_1_explanation>\n            }},\n            {{\n                \"summary\":<insight_2_summary>,\n                \"explanation\": <insight_2_explanation>\n            }}\n        ]\n    }}\n\n# Grounding Rules\n\nPoints supported by data should list their data references as follows:\n\n\"This is an example sentence supported by multiple data references [Data: <dataset name> (record ids); <dataset name> (record ids)].\"\n\nDo not list more than 5 record ids in a single reference. Instead, list the top 5 most relevant record ids and add \"+more\" to indicate that there are more.\n\nFor example:\n\"Person X is the owner of Company Y and subject to many allegations of wrongdoing [Data: Reports (1), Entities (5, 7); Relationships (23); Claims (7, 2, 34, 64, 46, +more)].\"\n\nwhere 1, 5, 7, 23, 2, 34, 46, and 64 represent the id (not the index) of the relevant data record.\n\nDo not include information where the supporting evidence for it is not provided.\n\n\n# Example Input\n-----------\nText:\n\nEntities\n\nid,entity,description\n5,VERDANT OASIS PLAZA,Verdant Oasis Plaza is the location of the Unity March\n6,HARMONY ASSEMBLY,Harmony Assembly is an organization that is holding a march at Verdant Oasis Plaza\n\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n37,VERDANT OASIS PLAZA,UNITY MARCH,Verdant Oasis Plaza is the location of the Unity March\n38,VERDANT OASIS PLAZA,HARMONY ASSEMBLY,Harmony Assembly is holding a march at Verdant Oasis Plaza\n39,VERDANT OASIS PLAZA,UNITY MARCH,The Unity March is taking place at Verdant Oasis Plaza\n40,VERDANT OASIS PLAZA,TRIBUNE SPOTLIGHT,Tribune Spotlight is reporting on the Unity march taking place at Verdant Oasis Plaza\n41,VERDANT OASIS PLAZA,BAILEY ASADI,Bailey Asadi is speaking at Verdant Oasis Plaza about the march\n43,HARMONY ASSEMBLY,UNITY MARCH,Harmony Assembly is organizing the Unity March\n\nOutput:\n{{\n    \"title\": \"Verdant Oasis Plaza and Unity March\",\n    \"summary\": \"The community revolves around the Verdant Oasis Plaza, which is the location of the Unity March. The plaza has relationships with the Harmony Assembly, Unity March, and Tribune Spotlight, all of which are associated with the march event.\",\n    \"rating\": 5.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is moderate due to the potential for unrest or conflict during the Unity March.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Verdant Oasis Plaza as the central location\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Verdant Oasis Plaza is the central entity in this community, serving as the location for the Unity March. This plaza is the common link between all other entities, suggesting its significance in the community. The plaza's association with the march could potentially lead to issues such as public disorder or conflict, depending on the nature of the march and the reactions it provokes. [Data: Entities (5), Relationships (37, 38, 39, 40, 41,+more)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Harmony Assembly's role in the community\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Harmony Assembly is another key entity in this community, being the organizer of the march at Verdant Oasis Plaza. The nature of Harmony Assembly and its march could be a potential source of threat, depending on their objectives and the reactions they provoke. The relationship between Harmony Assembly and the plaza is crucial in understanding the dynamics of this community. [Data: Entities(6), Relationships (38, 43)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Unity March as a significant event\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The Unity March is a significant event taking place at Verdant Oasis Plaza. This event is a key factor in the community's dynamics and could be a potential source of threat, depending on the nature of the march and the reactions it provokes. The relationship between the march and the plaza is crucial in understanding the dynamics of this community. [Data: Relationships (39)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Role of Tribune Spotlight\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Tribune Spotlight is reporting on the Unity March taking place in Verdant Oasis Plaza. This suggests that the event has attracted media attention, which could amplify its impact on the community. The role of Tribune Spotlight could be significant in shaping public perception of the event and the entities involved. [Data: Relationships (40)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\r\n2431,ADAPTATION DISORDER,\"Adaptation disorder is a mental health condition triggered by stressful life events, characterized by emotional and behavioral symptoms\",8\r\n624,PSYCHOTHERAPY,\"Psychotherapy is a comprehensive psychological treatment method employed by trained professionals to address a wide range of mental health conditions and disorders. It is utilized to treat depression, adaptation disorder, and sexual psychological disorders, including abnormal sexual behaviors. Techniques such as aversion conditioning therapy are applied to help patients form negative associations with harmful behaviors and restore natural functions. Psychotherapy also targets high-risk individuals and suicide survivors, providing psychological interventions to mitigate risks and promote recovery. The overarching goal of psychotherapy is to eliminate or reduce symptoms, regulate cognitive and behavioral patterns, enhance coping skills, reduce stress, and foster positive personality growth and development. This versatile approach makes it a vital tool in mental health care, tailored to meet the diverse needs of patients across various conditions.\",18\r\n140,CBT,\"Cognitive Behavioral Therapy, a psychological treatment used for phobias and other mental health conditions\",19\r\n643,PSYCHODYNAMIC THERAPY,\"Psychodynamic therapy is a form of psychotherapy that originates from psychoanalysis and is centered on exploring unconscious processes, past experiences, and unresolved conflicts to understand and treat mental health conditions. This therapeutic approach emphasizes the influence of childhood trauma and unconscious conflicts as root causes of psychological disorders, aiming to address current psychological issues by uncovering and resolving these underlying factors. Unlike behavior therapy, which focuses on modifying observable behaviors, psychodynamic therapy delves into the deeper, often hidden aspects of the psyche to foster insight and emotional healing. By examining the interplay between past experiences and present psychological challenges, psychodynamic therapy seeks to provide a comprehensive understanding of an individual's mental health and facilitate long-term therapeutic change.\",5\r\n640,COGNITIVE BEHAVIORAL THERAPY,\"Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT) is a widely recognized and effective psychological treatment method rooted in behavioral learning theory and cognitive psychology. It aims to address and modify dysfunctional cognitions, emotions, and behaviors through systematic, goal-oriented procedures. CBT is practical and versatile, focusing on identifying and changing negative thought patterns and behaviors to improve mental health and emotional well-being. It is particularly effective in treating a range of conditions, including depression, acute stress disorder, eating disorders, and adjustment disorders.  \n\nThe therapy involves monitoring automatic thoughts, helping patients identify irrational cognitions about stressors and their coping abilities, and rebuilding adaptive behaviors. It combines cognitive and behavioral techniques to process traumatic events, develop coping strategies, and address maladaptive thoughts and behaviors. CBT is often used in conjunction with medication and is tailored to treat specific behavioral issues, making it a comprehensive approach to mental health treatment. Its structured and evidence-based nature has established it as a cornerstone in psychotherapy for various mental disorders.\",21\r\n646,INTEGRATIVE THERAPY,Integrative therapy combines theories and techniques from different therapeutic approaches to create a new treatment system,4\r\n635,A. ELLIS,\"A. Ellis is a prominent figure in the field of psychotherapy, best known for creating Rational Emotive Behavior Therapy (REBT). REBT is a cognitive approach to psychotherapy that focuses on identifying and changing irrational beliefs and thought patterns to improve emotional well-being. As a precursor to Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT), REBT has had a significant influence on modern therapeutic practices. A. Ellis's work emphasizes the importance of rational thinking and emotional regulation in addressing psychological challenges.\",3\r\n2436,ESTAZOLAM,\"An anti-anxiety medication used to relieve anxiety, tension, and insomnia\"\"\",3\r\n636,A.T. BECK,\"A.T. Beck developed Cognitive Therapy, which later combined with behavior therapy to form Cognitive Behavioral Therapy.\"\"\",2\r\n712,COGNITIVE RESTRUCTURING,\"A therapeutic technique aimed at replacing negative, self-defeating thoughts with positive, self-reinforcing ones>\",2\r\n713,COGNITIVE DEMONSTRATION,A therapeutic method where the therapist models effective ways of thinking and behaving in specific situations to help the patient overcome self-defeating thoughts and behaviors>,1\r\n714,REALITY TESTING,A therapeutic technique involving homework assignments that challenge the patient's unrealistic or distorted beliefs through practical experience>,1\r\n700,MC. JONES,\"MC. Jones is credited with early work in behavior therapy, successfully treating a child's phobia in 1924.\",1\r\n701,I. PAVLOV,\"I. Pavlov is a behaviorist known for his work on classical conditioning, influencing early behavior therapy.\",1\r\n702,JB. WATSON,JB. Watson is a behaviorist who contributed to the development of behavior therapy through his work on behaviorism.,1\r\n703,CL. HULL,CL. Hull is a behaviorist whose theories influenced the development of behavior therapy techniques.,1\r\n704,BF. SKINNER,\"BF. Skinner is known for his work on operant conditioning, which influenced behavior therapy techniques for chronic psychiatric disorders.\",1\r\n705,AT. BECK,\"AT. Beck developed cognitive therapy, which later merged with behavior therapy to form CBT.\",1\r\n706,AA. LAZARUS,AA. Lazarus developed a broader spectrum of cognitive-behavioral therapy techniques.,1\r\n707,MEICHENBAUM,Meichenbaum is known for his work on cognitive-behavioral modification techniques.,1\r\n709,COGNITIVE THERAPY,\"Cognitive therapy, developed by AT. Beck, focuses on identifying and changing cognitive distortions and is a key component of CBT.\",1\r\n710,RATIONAL EMOTIVE BEHAVIOR THERAPY,\"Rational Emotive Behavior Therapy (REBT), developed by A. Ellis, is a form of cognitive-behavioral therapy that addresses irrational beliefs.\",1\r\n711,COGNITIVE REVOLUTION,\"The cognitive revolution in psychology shifted focus from behaviorism to cognitive processes, influencing the development of cognitive therapy and CBT.\",1\r\n631,FRITZ,\"Fritz, along with Perls, created Gestalt therapy, a humanistic approach to psychotherapy.\"\"\",1\r\n632,PERLS,\"Perls, along with Fritz, created Gestalt therapy, a humanistic approach to psychotherapy.\"\"\",1\r\n633,ROSENBERG,\"Rosenberg created Nonviolent Communication, a humanistic approach to psychotherapy.\"\"\",1\r\n634,BERNE,\"Berne created Transactional Analysis, a humanistic approach to psychotherapy.\"\"\",1\r\n2470,AVERSION CONDITIONING THERAPY,\"A type of behavioral therapy where patients are exposed to unpleasant stimuli when they imagine or engage in abnormal sexual behaviors, helping them form negative associations and reduce such behaviors\",1\r\n642,ROGERS,\"Rogers is widely recognized as the founder of client-centered therapy, a significant and representative approach within humanistic therapy. Central to his therapeutic philosophy is the emphasis on key therapist attitudes that foster a successful therapeutic relationship. These attitudes include congruence, which refers to the therapist’s authenticity and genuineness; unconditional positive regard, which involves accepting and valuing the client without judgment; and empathy, which entails deeply understanding and sharing the client’s feelings. Rogers’ client-centered therapy prioritizes creating a warm, empathetic, and nonjudgmental environment, enabling clients to explore their emotions and experiences freely. His contributions have had a profound impact on the field of psychotherapy, shaping the way therapists approach their relationships with clients.\",5\r\n644,HUMANISTIC THERAPY,\"**Humanistic Therapy** is a psychological approach that emphasizes the uniqueness of individuals and their inherent ability to control their own destiny. Central to this therapy is the concept of self-actualization, which encourages individuals to realize their full potential and achieve personal growth. Humanistic therapy includes various approaches, with **client-centered therapy** being a prominent example. This approach focuses on creating a supportive and non-judgmental environment that fosters self-exploration and development. Overall, Humanistic Therapy prioritizes the individual's subjective experience and their capacity for self-directed change, aiming to empower them in their journey toward personal fulfillment.\",7\r\n987,DIAZEPAM,\"Diazepam is a benzodiazepine medication primarily used as an anti-anxiety agent to relieve symptoms of anxiety, tension, and insomnia. It is also effective in managing other conditions, such as controlling seizures, particularly in cases of poisoning. As a benzodiazepine, Diazepam works by enhancing the effects of certain neurotransmitters in the brain, promoting relaxation and reducing overactivity in the nervous system. However, its use is associated with potential side effects, including drowsiness and the risk of dependence, especially with prolonged use. Overall, Diazepam serves as a versatile medication for anxiety-related disorders and seizure management, though it requires careful monitoring to mitigate its side effects and risks.\",5\r\n645,SYSTEMIC THERAPY,\"Systemic therapy, including family and marital therapy, focuses on the relationship systems and dynamics that contribute to psychological issues\",2\r\n2434,STRESSFUL LIFE EVENTS,,1\r\n2433,PHARMACOLOGICAL TREATMENT,\"Pharmacological treatment involves the use of medications, such as anti-anxiety drugs, to alleviate symptoms of adaptation disorder\",1\r\n692,CLIENT-CENTERED THERAPY,\"**Client-centered therapy**, developed by Carl Rogers, is a psychological approach that emphasizes the therapist's attitudes of congruence, unconditional positive regard, and empathy as essential components to facilitate the client's self-actualization and self-esteem. This non-directive therapeutic method places the primary responsibility for the therapeutic process on the client, encouraging self-exploration and personal growth. The goal of client-centered therapy is to help clients achieve greater self-understanding and self-acceptance, fostering an environment where individuals can feel supported and empowered to navigate their own path to healing and development.\",3\r\n627,J. WOLPE,\"J. Wolpe is a prominent figure in the field of behaviorism, renowned for his contributions to behavior therapy and the development of systematic desensitization. Systematic desensitization, a technique he pioneered, is a widely used behavior therapy method for treating phobias. This approach is grounded in the principles of classical conditioning, which Wolpe effectively applied to help individuals gradually reduce their anxiety responses to specific stimuli. Additionally, his work in behaviorism has significantly influenced the creation of various behavior modification techniques, which are based on both classical and operant conditioning principles. Overall, J. Wolpe's contributions have had a lasting impact on the field of psychology, particularly in the treatment of anxiety disorders and the advancement of behavior therapy.\",3\r\n638,BEHAVIORISM,\"Behaviorism is a psychological approach that emerged in the 20th century, focusing on the study and modification of behavior through techniques rooted in classical and operant conditioning. This approach emphasizes the role of environmental factors in shaping behavior, highlighting the influence of external stimuli and reinforcement mechanisms. Behaviorism is often contrasted with humanistic therapy, which places greater emphasis on internal experiences and personal growth. By prioritizing observable and measurable behaviors, behaviorism seeks to understand and alter behavior through systematic, evidence-based methods.\",4\r\n628,H. EYSENCK,\"H. Eysenck was a prominent psychologist and a key figure in the field of behaviorism. He made significant contributions to behavior therapy, particularly in the development of techniques for treating neurotic disorders. His work was grounded in the principles of classical and operant conditioning, which he utilized to create effective behavior modification strategies. Eysenck's influence extended beyond theoretical contributions, as his practical applications of behavior therapy had a lasting impact on the treatment of psychological conditions.\",3\r\n629,B.F. SKINNER,\"B.F. Skinner is a key figure in behaviorism, which created behavior modification techniques based on classical and operant conditioning.\"\"\",2\r\n699,HUMAN POTENTIAL MOVEMENT,,1\r\n2232,SLEEP APNEA SYNDROME,\"Sleep Apnea Syndrome is a disorder involving repeated episodes of breathing cessation during sleep, often accompanied by loud snoring and daytime sleepiness, and can lead to serious health complications\",1\r\n2236,HYPERSOMNIA,,5\r\n2233,PICKWICKIAN SYNDROME,\"Pickwickian Syndrome is a condition characterized by obesity, hypoventilation, and sleep apnea, leading to significant respiratory and cardiovascular issues\",1\r\n2234,STIMULANT MEDICATIONS,\"Stimulant Medications, such as methylphenidate and amphetamines, are used to treat conditions like hypersomnia by promoting wakefulness and reducing excessive sleepiness\",1\r\n2235,SSRI MEDICATIONS,\"SSRI Medications, including fluoxetine, paroxetine, and sertraline, are used in the treatment of hypersomnia and other sleep-related disorders due to their effects on serotonin levels\",1\r\n2435,ALPRAZOLAM,\"An anti-anxiety medication used to relieve anxiety, tension, and insomnia\"\"\",3\r\n696,KURT LEWIN,\"Kurt Lewin is a renowned psychologist recognized for his significant contributions to the fields of group dynamics and sensitivity training. In the 1940s, he developed T-group training, a method that has had a profound influence on group therapy techniques. His work in this area also played a pivotal role in shaping Carl Rogers' use of encounter groups within client-centered therapy. Lewin's innovative approaches to understanding and improving group interactions have left a lasting impact on both psychological theory and practice.\",3\r\n698,SENSITIVITY TRAINING,\"Sensitivity training, pioneered by Kurt Lewin, was a method used in group dynamics and influenced Rogers' use of encounter groups in client-centered therapy\",2\r\n693,ABRAHAM MASLOW,\"Abraham Maslow is a humanistic psychologist known for his theory of the hierarchy of needs, which culminates in self-actualization. He believed psychological issues stem from difficulties in meeting self-esteem needs.\",2\r\n695,HIERARCHY OF NEEDS,Maslow's hierarchy of needs is a theory that describes human motivation as a progression from basic physiological needs to self-actualization.,2\r\n697,ENCOUNTER GROUP,\"Encounter groups, a technique used by Rogers, were influenced by sensitivity training and aimed at fostering personal growth and self-awareness\",2\r\n708,CORMIER,\"CORMIER is a notable therapist recognized for his significant contributions to the field of cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT). He is best known for developing cognitive restructuring therapy, a core component of CBT, which focuses on identifying and altering negative thought patterns. In 1991, CORMIER proposed a structured six-step process for cognitive restructuring, providing a practical framework for therapists and clients to effectively address and modify maladaptive thinking. His work has had a lasting impact on the practice of psychotherapy, particularly in the treatment of cognitive distortions and emotional disorders.\",2\r\n625,RHAZES,\"Rhazes developed theory-based, goal-oriented psychotherapy in the 9th century at Baghdad's psychiatric hospital.\"\"\",2\r\n641,BAGHDAD,,1\r\n630,C. ROGERS,\"C. Rogers created client-centered therapy, a humanistic approach focusing on supporting individuals to achieve self-actualization.\"\"\",2\r\n639,EXISTENTIAL-HUMANISTIC THERAPY,\"Existential-Humanistic Therapy is a psychological approach that emerged in the 20th century, focusing on personal growth, self-actualization, and finding meaning in life.\"\"\",1\r\n694,SELF-ACTUALIZATION,\"Self-actualization is the process of realizing one's full potential, a central concept in humanistic therapy and Maslow's hierarchy of needs.\",1\r\n756,PERSONALITY DISORDERS,\"A psychiatric condition where psychological and biological factors converge, involving both inherited temperament and character shaped by environment and education\nA group of mental health conditions characterized by enduring maladaptive patterns of behavior, cognition, and inner experience, often treated with psychotherapy\",2\r\n758,PSYCHOLOGICAL TREATMENT,,1\r\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,combined_degree\r\n2845,ADAPTATION DISORDER,DEPRESSION,Adaptation disorder and depression share similar symptoms but differ in severity and duration,63\r\n726,PSYCHOTHERAPY,FREUD,\"Freud developed psychoanalysis, the first scientific psychotherapy, which laid the foundation for modern psychotherapy.\",47\r\n173,CBT,恐惧症,\"CBT is a common treatment for 恐惧症, helping individuals manage their fears\",33\r\n751,PSYCHODYNAMIC THERAPY,COGNITIVE BEHAVIORAL THERAPY,\"Both are major therapeutic approaches in psychology, though they differ in theory and technique\",26\r\n753,COGNITIVE BEH